President Donald Trump and Philippine President Rodrigo Duterte met in Manila to discuss shared interests and priorities. They praised the United States-Philippines Alliance and pledged to strengthen the bilateral alliance. They commended the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) for promoting regional peace and development. Both leaders condemned North Korea's nuclear weapons and missile development and called for compliance with UN Security Council Resolutions. President Trump expressed condolences for the loss of life in Marawi City and vowed continued support in the fight against terrorism. They reaffirmed their commitment to the Mutual Defense Treaty and discussed proposals to support the modernization of the Armed Forces of the Philippines. They also discussed the South China Sea dispute and the crisis in Rakhine State, Myanmar. The leaders pledged to deepen the economic relationship and explore strengthening innovation and technology cooperation. They also discussed the ongoing campaign against illegal drugs and emphasized the importance of people-to-people connections and inclusive development. The two presidents pledged to continue cooperating for peace and prosperity in the Asia-Pacific region.